  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real phenomenon that affects many students, especially those from underrepresented groups. I've seen it firsthand in my own community. Back in my day, as a young man growing up in Chicago, I remember how the idea that 'only smart people go into engineering' made some kids shy away from math and science. It wasn't just about being smart—it was about the fear of being labeled as not good enough. When I was a boy, my dad, who had a vocational diploma, would tell me that if I was interested in building things, I should focus on practical skills. But that same fear of being seen as 'not smart enough' could make a kid give up before they even started. I've heard stories from my grandchildren about how some girls in their schools get nervous about math tests because they worry they'll prove they're not as good as boys. This is why addressing stereotype threat is so important. We need to create environments where everyone feels safe to try and fail without judgment. As a curious person who's spent time in the community, I believe we can help by encouraging kids to see STEM as a place where everyone belongs, not just a select few. It's about building confidence and showing that intelligence isn't fixed—it's something you can grow. My own experience as a carpenter taught me that skills come from practice and patience, not just innate talent. So, instead of labeling kids as 'good' or 'bad' at science, we should help them see that they can learn and improve. This isn't about changing the system overnight—it's about small steps, like teachers who are patient and supportive, or parents who encourage their children to explore without fear.",
